# Multi-agent systems

- Define each agent's role, tools, and boundaries explicitly — no overlapping responsibilities.
- Use a supervisor/orchestrator pattern for complex workflows; avoid uncontrolled agent-to-agent loops.
- Cap iteration count and tool calls per agent run to prevent runaway costs.
- Pass structured state between agents (JSON), not raw conversation history when possible.
- Give agents narrow tool sets — fewer tools = fewer hallucinated tool calls.
- Implement shared memory carefully: prefer explicit handoff documents over global mutable state.
- Log every agent step: input, tools called, output, tokens, latency.
- Test multi-agent flows with deterministic mocks before live LLM integration.
- Fail gracefully: if one agent fails, return partial results with clear error context.
- Start with single-agent + tools; add agents only when a clear separation of concerns exists.
